Welcome back to The Best & The Brightest. I=E2=80=99m Tara
Palmeri.

=C2=A0

In tonight=E2=80=99s issue, my conversation with Raheem Kassam, the former =
longtime Nigel Farage deputy and newish editor-in-chief of The National Pul=
se. I met Kassam nearly nine years ago at the United Kingdom Independence P=
arty conference in Doncaster=E2=80=94a former Labour town you=E2=80=99ve pr=
obably never heard of=E2=80=94where I was covering Brexit for Politico Euro=
pe.
Kassam and I witnessed the first wave of the populist movement in 2016 with=
 Britain=E2=80=99s exit from the E.U. amid a surge of anti-immigration sent=
iment.

When we reunited this week on my podcast, Somebody=E2=80=99s Gotta Win, Kas=
sam didn=E2=80=99t hold back in his criticism of Elon Musk=E2=80=99s plans =
for European domination and his recent social media assault on his old boss=
 Farage, who was hoping to win some Musk bucks for his Reform UK party. Far=
age was uncharacteristically at a loss
for words when Elon called on him to step down, saying that he was =E2=80=
=9Csurprised=E2=80=9D to hear this from someone he has called a =E2=80=9Cfr=
iend.=E2=80=9D Kassam=E2=80=99s thoughts, below the fold.=C2=A0=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But first, here=E2=80=99s Abby with an update on A.O.C.=E2=80=99s ongoing r=
edemption tour=E2=80=A6

Abby Livingston
Abby Livingston

=E2=80=8A

A.O.C.=E2=80=99s House Tour
---------------------

Earlier today, House Democrats finally named
Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez to the House Energy and Commerce Committee, a trop=
hy she=E2=80=99s pursued for much of her still relatively nascent, vertigin=
ous political career. While this might seem like a consolation prize after =
her failed bid for the top minority slot on House Oversight, A.O.C. has pai=
d her dues=E2=80=94both figuratively and literally. It was only four years =
ago that she
lost ( https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/kathleen-rice-picked-over-=
ocasio-cortez-spot-house-energy-commerce-n1251640?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%=
26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F7%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+=
The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F7%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_=
source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) a bid to join this ver=
y committee to Kathleen Rice, a now-retired New York Democratic rebel who l=
earned to successfully play the inside game. Now, A.O.C. seems to be follow=
ing a similar trajectory. =E2=80=9CShe=E2=80=99s entering her fourth term n=
ow; she=E2=80=99s making amends for past perceived sins; she=E2=80=99s play=
ing the
game smarter,=E2=80=9D former Democratic Rep. Cheri Bustos told me.

=C2=A0

Even based purely on seniority, it was well past time for A.O.C. to land an=
 =E2=80=9CA=E2=80=9D committee slot. (She=E2=80=99s the most senior among t=
he new Dems slated so far to join her on E&C.) Meanwhile, the Oversight rac=
e, which she lost to Gerry Connolly, only increased her standing in the cau=
cus. Indeed, the final
tally=E2=80=94131 to 84=E2=80=94demonstrated that dozens of House Democrats=
 consider her a member of the team. It also didn=E2=80=99t hurt that last y=
ear, for the first time, she paid $250,000 to the D.C.C.C. to help vulnerab=
le colleagues. Given all of this, it=E2=80=99s fair to assume she=E2=80=99s=
 the frontrunner to lead Oversight once Connolly retires. If she sticks aro=
und, the 36-year-old potentially has decades to move up the seniority ladde=
r at E&C, and could therefore end up serving as the chair of not one, but t=
wo
committees.=C2=A0

Ironically, A.O.C.=E2=80=99s career is starting to resemble those of two re=
cent Republican powerhouses. Back in the aughts, Paul Ryan was something of=
 an A.O.C.-ish phenom, himself, capturing the hearts and minds of the Gen X=
 and millennial Alex P. Keatons of the G.O.P. (He=E2=80=99d also
spent ( https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/from-capitol-hill-tex-mex-w=
aiter-to-54th-speaker-of-the-house/2015/10/29/54b1e8a4-7e61-11e5-afce-2afd1=
d3eb896_story.html?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+=
%281%2F7%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%28=
1%2F7%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=
=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) enough time in his youth working as a Hill staffer =
and as a waiter at Tortilla Coast to grasp Capitol Hill politics more quick=
ly than A.O.C. did.) The other is Patrick McHenry, the just-retired North C=
arolina Republican who entered Congress as a
conservative rebel in 2005, but retired as the Financial Services chairman,=
 after proving to be the glue that held the conference together amid its sp=
eakerless October of 2023.

Of course, the perpetual question in New York politics is whether A.O.C. wi=
ll run for Senate, the presidency, or both. For most members, the House is =
the lowliest rung in national politics=E2=80=94but there are a handful who =
could have run for Senate at some point but chose instead to remain in the =
lower chamber,
eventually attaining positions as powerful as those of any statewide offici=
al. (Nancy Pelosi and Ryan were third in line to the presidency.) Looking a=
t her career from the committee angle, perhaps there=E2=80=99s logic to her=
 sticking around.

