Not content to limit his meddling to U.S. politics, the world=E2=80=99s
richest man has turned his sights overseas=E2=80=94tweaking the left in Ger=
many and going full Farage in Britain. But as the international MAGA ambass=
ador Raheem Kassam explains, Musk=E2=80=99s games are already alienating wo=
uld-be allies.=C2=A0

Tara Palmeri ( https://puck.news/author/tara-palmeri/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Be=
st+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F7%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+=
%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F7%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&=
utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Tara Palmeri ( https://puck.news/author/tara-palmeri/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Be=
st+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F7%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+=
%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F7%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&=
utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Having successfully inserted himself into U.S. politics,
Elon Musk is now turning an eye toward a few of the major powers in Europe=
=E2=80=94namely, Germany and the U.K. In recent days, he endorsed Germany=
=E2=80=99s far-right AfD party, whose leader he plans to host on an X lives=
tream this week; and last week, he spent several days on the platform attac=
king Keir Starmer, Britain=E2=80=99s Labour prime minister. He simultaneous=
ly praised the right-wing populist Reform UK party of Nigel Farage, the Bre=
xit
artist who has become a fairly common sight at Mar-a-Lago, while also sayin=
g Farage =E2=80=9Cdoesn=E2=80=99t have what it takes=E2=80=9D to lead the p=
arty=E2=80=A6 just hours after Farage described Musk as a =E2=80=9Cfriend=
=E2=80=9D in an interview on the BBC. Heavy stuff.

=C2=A0

For more on Elon=E2=80=99s meddling, I rang up Raheem Kassam, a former advi=
sor to Farage and editor of The National Pulse who has become a fixture in =
the MAGA
multiverse with strong opinions on trans-Atlantic populism. Interestingly, =
despite his former affinity for Musk, Kassam now believes that the world=E2=
=80=99s richest man is having a deleterious effect on politics writ large. =
Kassam and I discussed it all on my podcast, Somebody=E2=80=99s Gotta Win (=
 https://puck.news/podcast_episode/elon-eyes-european-domination-with-rahee=
m-kassam/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F7%=
2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F7%2F2=
5%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617=
da42abd12a ). In this lightly edited excerpt, he explains why Elon is
taking an interest in the U.K., what he doesn=E2=80=99t grasp about Farage,=
 and why he should keep his fortune out of British politics.=C2=A0

The Farage-Elon Sitch
---------------------

Tara Palmeri: Why is Elon Musk
suddenly so interested in the U.K.?

=C2=A0

Raheem Kassam: What does the man with all the money in the world want? He d=
oesn=E2=80=99t want more money; he wants more power. You see this in Italy =
at the moment, with his capture of [Prime Minister] Giorgia Meloni. I=E2=80=
=99ve known Giorgia for the better part of a decade, and she=E2=80=99s comp=
letely changed as a result of Elon=E2=80=99s
involvement with her. You=E2=80=99ll see that with Trump as well. I want to=
 make it clear: I actually think the Reform party should refuse any advance=
s and cash from Elon Musk.

=C2=A0

So you=E2=80=99ve changed your mind?

=C2=A0

Here=E2=80=99s the thing: 100 million dollars, or 100 million pounds, is eq=
uivalent to
five election cycles in the U.K. Most parties spend about 15 to 20 million =
dollars on an election cycle; it=E2=80=99s not like here [in the U.S.], whe=
re you spend $1 billion. I have changed my mind, having seen how he=E2=80=
=99s behaved. I always use [George] Soros as the example: Before Soros come=
s along and starts stroking checks to the Democratic Party, the Democratic =
Party still considers itself a pro-American worker, pro-union, antiwar part=
y. Then suddenly, all of
these corporate donors=E2=80=94of which Soros is probably the most identifi=
able=E2=80=94come along and fundamentally change the party.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

To avoid something like that, you have to keep big-money interests out of y=
our political parties and out of your political movements. I keep telling R=
epublicans, =E2=80=9CYou can knock down Kevin McCarthy, you can knock down =
Mike Johnson, you can knock down
Tom Emmer. But unless you get the money out of that situation, all of these=
 people lining up are going to be the same person.=E2=80=9D They=E2=80=99re=
 just a facsimile of the wider problem. That=E2=80=99s something I don=E2=
=80=99t want in British politics, and Elon has shown himself to be that guy=
=2E

=C2=A0

You liked Elon Musk for a while; you were actually a proponent of his.

=C2=A0

I don=E2=80=99t know if I=E2=80=99d go that far. I wouldn=E2=80=99t say pro=
ponent. I was definitely somebody who cheered him on when he seemed to be g=
oing in the right direction=E2=80=94but I stopped as soon as he stopped goi=
ng in that direction. I=E2=80=99m more than happy to call balls and strikes=
 when I see them. People on the left will say he=E2=80=99s dangerous for de=
mocracy. That may well be true. I would say he=E2=80=99s dangerous for the =
political right worldwide.

=C2=A0

Nigel Farage has called Elon a hero and said he=E2=80=99s pleased Elon is b=
acking the Reform party. I have a hard time imagining anyone but Nigel lead=
ing the party. So what=E2=80=99s the current beef between Farage and Elon?

=C2=A0

Elon likes to collect people. And he thought he was on his way to collect N=
igel Farage, but he doesn=E2=80=99t work like
that. People have come to him with big checkbooks before and asked him to c=
hange his position on Brexit. That=E2=80=99s just not who he is. He=E2=80=
=99s always been his own man. He=E2=80=99s probably even more independent-m=
inded than Donald Trump. Nigel has been doing this since the early =E2=80=
=9990s, whereas Trump is still quite new to politics in the grand scheme of=
 things. Musk=E2=80=99s kind of dug in on this issue of the grooming gangs,=
 Keir Starmer=E2=80=94all of this stuff is being weaponized in a way that i=
s really
terrible. I say this as a person who helped Tommy Robinson out of prison in=
 2018. This is a street activist who is now in prison, who Elon is champion=
ing in a big way on X. And this is where the fight really lies. Elon is try=
ing to push Tommy Robinson as a figure on Nigel Farage and the Reform party=
, without understanding that there=E2=80=99s a longstanding animosity betwe=
en those men that will push Nigel Farage away from Elon Musk in a greater w=
ay than Elon could ever understand. And
that shows how green Elon is to all of this stuff.

The Carve-Out
-------------

Farage has said he wants to be the intermediary between the
U.K. government and Trump. That he=E2=80=99s frequently seen at Mar-a-Lago =
and in Washington obviously heightens his profile. But a U.K. representativ=
e has dismissed the idea. So why is Farage hanging out with Trump all the t=
ime? Unless he just wants to be relevant and famous and get elected?

=C2=A0

Well, Nigel Farage is already very famous, at least in the United Kingdom. =
So he doesn=E2=80=99t really need that. What he
needs is the legitimacy of having the global superpower=E2=80=99s leader, t=
he leader of the free world, endorsing him, as Trump just did. I was emceei=
ng the New York Young Republican gala over Christmas, and Trump sent not on=
e, but two videos endorsing Nigel.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Nigel understands he can parlay that power into electoral relevance in the =
United Kingdom. And it=E2=80=99s done him a great lot of good to be seen wi=
th and
around Donald Trump. It has cut the rug out from underneath the Conservativ=
e Party and its leader, Kemi Badenoch. It causes the Labour Party all sorts=
 of problems because they don=E2=80=99t know what Trump is back-channeling =
to Nigel, and vice versa. Nigel wants to serve his country in any way he ca=
n. So if Peter Mandelson, or whoever=E2=80=99s going to be the next British=
 ambassador to the U.S., comes along and asks for his help, he=E2=80=99ll h=
elp them. The problem is, the political
establishment in Britain doesn=E2=80=99t want to give [Farage] that credenc=
e and that credibility, because that elevates him further and almost makes =
him the prime minister in waiting.

=C2=A0

The U.K. could find itself in a precarious situation, given Trump=E2=80=99s=
 tariffs and his statements that the U.S. should lower its security commitm=
ent to Europe. How great of a threat do you think this poses to the U.K.=E2=
=80=94and is
there any way Nigel Farage could save the day?

=C2=A0

Yes, absolutely. To my understanding, there have already been conversations=
 about carve-outs for the United Kingdom. We know that Trump obviously has =
a soft spot for the U.K. Brexit allowed the U.K. government to go out and m=
ake its own tailored trade deals with individual nation states, and indeed,=
 with the E.U. itself. The problem is the
Conservative Party and Labour Party have had no interest in doing that. The=
 incoming Trump administration has the ability to make Brexit a functional =
success by agreeing to just one bilateral trade deal.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

I think they=E2=80=99ll do it, and I think it will be done because Nigel Fa=
rage keeps popping up at Mar-a-Lago and talking to the right people about t=
his=E2=80=94he=E2=80=99ll never get the credit he deserves. But that will a=
meliorate any
Brexit regret that lingers, and it will allow the country to move into a ne=
w economic prosperity period. If Nigel can convince Trump to have that carv=
e-out, especially on the tariff regime, he=E2=80=99ll be an international h=
ero.=C2=A0

