line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong><em>Tara Palmeri</em></strong><strong>:=
 Why is Elon Musk
suddenly so interested in the U.K.?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin=
-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><em>Raheem=
 Kassam</em>: What does the man with all the money in the world want? He do=
esn=E2=80=99t want more money; he wants more power. You see this in Italy a=
t the moment, with his capture of [Prime Minister] <strong>Giorgia Meloni</=
strong>. I=E2=80=99ve known Giorgia for the better part of a decade, and sh=
e=E2=80=99s completely changed as a result of <strong>Elon</strong>=E2=80=
=99s
involvement with her. You=E2=80=99ll see that with <strong>Trump </strong>a=
s well. I want to make it clear: I actually think the Reform party should r=
efuse any advances and cash from Elon Musk.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-=
bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>So =
you=E2=80=99ve changed your mind?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Here=E2=80=
=99s the thing: 100 million dollars, or 100 million pounds, is equivalent t=
o
<em>five</em> election cycles in the U.K. Most parties spend about 15 to 20=
 million dollars on an election cycle; it=E2=80=99s not like here [in the U=
=2ES.], where you spend $1 billion. I h=
ave changed my mind, having seen how h=
e=E2=80=99s behaved. I always use [<strong>George</strong>] <strong>Soros <=
/strong>as the example: Before Soros comes along and starts stroking checks=
 to the Democratic Party, the Democratic Party still considers itself a pro=
-American worker, pro-union, antiwar party. Then suddenly, all of
these corporate donors=E2=80=94of which Soros is probably the most identifi=
able=E2=80=94come along and fundamentally change the party.=C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">To avoid something like that, you have to keep big-money interes=
ts out of your political parties and out of your political movements. I kee=
p telling Republicans, =E2=80=9CYou can knock down <strong>Kevin McCarthy</=
strong>, you can knock down <strong>Mike Johnson</strong>, you can knock do=
wn
<strong>Tom Emmer</strong>. But unless you get the money out of that situat=
ion, all of these people lining up are going to be the same person.=E2=80=
=9D They=E2=80=99re just a facsimile of the wider problem. That=E2=80=99s s=
omething I don=E2=80=99t want in British politics, and Elon has shown himse=
lf to be that guy.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>You liked Elon Musk for a wh=
ile; you were actually a proponent of his.</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I do=
n=E2=80=99t know if I=E2=80=99d go that far. I wouldn=E2=80=99t say <em>pro=
ponent</em>. I was definitely somebody who cheered him on when he seemed to=
 be going in the right direction=E2=80=94but I stopped as soon as he stoppe=
d going in that direction. I=E2=80=99m more than happy to call balls and st=
rikes when I see them. People on the left will say he=E2=80=99s dangerous f=
or democracy. That may well be true. I would say he=E2=80=99s dangerous for=
 the political right worldwide.</p>
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Nigel Farage has called Elon a hero and said he=E2=
=80=99s pleased Elon is backing the Reform party. I have a hard time imagin=
ing anyone but Nigel leading the party. So what=E2=80=99s the current beef =
between Farage and Elon?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px=
;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Elon likes to collect people. And he th=
ought he was on his way to collect Nigel Farage, but he doesn=E2=80=99t wor=
k like
that. People have come to him with big checkbooks before and asked him to c=
hange his position on Brexit. That=E2=80=99s just not who he is. He=E2=80=
=99s always been his own man. He=E2=80=99s probably even more independent-m=
inded than Donald Trump. Nigel has been doing this since the early =E2=80=
=9990s, whereas Trump is still quite new to politics in the grand scheme of=
 things. Musk=E2=80=99s kind of dug in on this issue of the grooming gangs,=
 Keir Starmer=E2=80=94all of this stuff is being weaponized in a way that i=
s really
terrible. I say this as a person who helped <strong>Tommy Robinson</strong>=
 out of prison in 2018. This is a street activist who is now in prison, who=
 Elon is championing in a big way on X. And this is where the fight really =
lies. Elon is trying to push Tommy Robinson as a figure on Nigel Farage and=
 the Reform party, without understanding that there=E2=80=99s a longstandin=
g animosity between those men that will push Nigel Farage away from Elon Mu=
sk in a greater way than Elon could ever understand. And
that shows how green Elon is to all of this stuff.</p></div>
