ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Farage has said he wants to be the inte=
rmediary between the
U.K. government and Trump. That he=E2=80=99s frequently seen at Mar-a-Lago =
and in Washington obviously heightens his profile. But a U.K. representativ=
e has dismissed the idea. So why is Farage hanging out with Trump all the t=
ime? Unless he just wants to be relevant and famous and get elected?</stron=
g></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin=
:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Well, Nigel Farage is already very famous, at least =
in the United Kingdom. So he doesn=E2=80=99t really need that. What he
needs is the legitimacy of having the global superpower=E2=80=99s leader, t=
he leader of the free world, endorsing him, as Trump just did. I was emceei=
ng the New York Young Republican gala over Christmas, and Trump sent not on=
e, but two videos endorsing Nigel.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bot=
tom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Nigel understa=
nds he can parlay that power into electoral relevance in the United Kingdom=
=2E And it=E2=80=99s done him a great lot of good to be seen with and
around Donald Trump. It has cut the rug out from underneath the Conservativ=
e Party and its leader, <strong>Kemi Badenoch</strong>. It causes the Labou=
r Party all sorts of problems because they don=E2=80=99t know what Trump is=
 back-channeling to Nigel, and vice versa. Nigel wants to serve his country=
 in any way he can. So if <strong>Peter Mandelson</strong>, or whoever=E2=
=80=99s going to be the next British ambassador to the U.S., comes along an=
d asks for his help, he=E2=80=99ll help them. The problem is, the political
establishment in Britain doesn=E2=80=99t want to give [Farage] that credenc=
e and that credibility, because that elevates him further and almost makes =
him the prime minister in waiting.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>The U.K. cou=
ld find itself in a precarious situation, given Trump=E2=80=99s tariffs and=
 his statements that the U.S. should lower its security commitment to Europ=
e. How great of a threat do you think this poses to the U.K.=E2=80=94and is
there any way Nigel Farage could save the day?</strong></p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"=
>Yes, absolutely. To my understanding, there have already been conversation=
s about carve-outs for the United Kingdom. We know that Trump obviously has=
 a soft spot for the U.K. Brexit allowed the U.K. government to go out and =
make its own tailored trade deals with individual nation states, and indeed=
, with the E.U. itself. The problem is the
Conservative Party and Labour Party have had no interest in doing that. The=
 incoming Trump administration has the ability to make Brexit a functional =
success by agreeing to just one bilateral trade deal.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"=
margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">I think they=
=E2=80=99ll do it, and I think it will be done because Nigel Farage keeps p=
opping up at Mar-a-Lago and talking to the right people about this=E2=80=94=
he=E2=80=99ll never get the credit he deserves. But that will ameliorate an=
y
Brexit regret that lingers, and it will allow the country to move into a ne=
w economic prosperity period. If Nigel can convince Trump to have that carv=
e-out, especially on the tariff regime, he=E2=80=99ll be an international h=
ero.=C2=A0</p></div>
